Inflation has a positive but insignificant effect on GDP growth.
Unemployment has a significant positive effect on GDP growth at the 1% significance level.
Population growth has a significant positive effect on GDP growth at the 1% significance level.
Rainfall has a significant negative effect on GDP growth at the 5% significance level.
Temperature has a significant positive effect on GDP growth at the 5% significance level.
Carbon emissions have a significant negative effect on GDP growth at the 1% significance level.

The error correction model produced an error correction coefficient for cointegrating equation [(denoted as CointEq (-1)], which was -1.79 and highly significant at the 1% level. Negative and significant implies long-term relationship exists between the dependent variable and the regressors. The coefficient is from the ARDL model which covers 1990-2019.

An exogenous shock to any independent variable (carbon emissions, rainfall, temperature, inflation, population, unemployment) did not have a detectable effect on GDP growth during the study period (1990-2019) based on Impulse Response Function analysis.
Variance Decomposition shows that economic growth demonstrated a descending trend within a 10-period horizon. Value is trending down (assigned -1 for descending).

Variance Decomposition shows that carbon emissions responded relatively well to economic growth dynamics within a 10-period horizon. Value is positively correlated (assigned 1 for positive correlation).
Variance Decomposition shows that unemployment responded relatively well to economic growth dynamics within a 10-period horizon. Value is positively correlated (assigned 1 for positive correlation).
Variance Decomposition shows that inflation responded relatively well to economic growth dynamics within a 10-period horizon. Value is positively correlated (assigned 1 for positive correlation).
Variance Decomposition shows that the response of rainfall to economic growth was not decisive within a 10-period horizon. Assigned 0 for no decisive trend.
Variance Decomposition shows that the response of temperature to economic growth was not decisive within a 10-period horizon. Assigned 0 for no decisive trend.
Variance Decomposition shows that the response of population to economic growth was not decisive within a 10-period horizon. Assigned 0 for no decisive trend.
